Workshop 2 - Code Repositories and Regular Expressions

Joseph Williamson

2022

A Workshop of Two Halves

In the first half we will be setting up our code repositories in GitHub, before learning about searching through text-based data using regular expressions in the second half.

1. Git and GitHub

By now you should hopefully have some idea about what Git and GitHub are, and why we might be keen to use them as data scientists. You should also have already created your own GitHub account. We now need to connect that GitHub account to the BIO319 GitHub Classroom, and then connect that to our Posit Cloud account.

1.1. GitHub Classroom

First, click on the following link to join our new GitHub classroom - GitHub Classroom Invite.

Find your name on the list to link your GitHub account to.

You will then be prompted to accept the assignment which will create a repository of all the files you need for today’s workshop (you may need to refresh the page after a few seconds for the repository to finish being created).

Click on the created hyperlink to be directed to your shiny new repo in the ‘Queen-Mary-University-London-BIO319’ organisation page. Copy the link to your new repository so that we can connect it to Posit Cloud.

1.2. Connecting Posit Cloud

You must now go and click on your profile in the top right of Posit Cloud and go to authentication.

Location of the authentication button in Posit Cloud

Next, enable GitHub and enable private repo access. You will be prompted by GitHub whether you want to authorise RStudio two times - once for each of the check boxes.

How to enable GitHub in Posit Cloud

Navigate your way back to the Posit Cloud ‘BIO319 2023 Workspace’ and click the ‘New Project’ drop down list in the top right, selecting ‘New Project from Git Repository’.

Button to select new project based off a Git repository

Paste in the Git repository that you copied earlier and hit ‘OK’. If you no longer have the repository, go to the ‘Queen-Mary-University-London-BIO319’ organisation page to find your new repository again.

Insert your Git repository in the box and hit OK

This should have set you up in a new project with all the files you will need for the rest of today’s workshop. Try opening up ‘Workshop2.html’ from the files pane to find the rest of your instructions for today’s session!
